Day 21 - Golden badge obtained! 2 days left until Thanksgiving, 8 days left until the end.

Awesome job as always soldiers! I wanna apologize for yesterday, I miscounted the days until the golden badge, but surprise! Chief replaced our dusty old silver badges with some nice & shiny gold ones! So congrats to everyone who has made it this far, let's have a moment of motivation.

When you're thinking of losing NNN, place the idea in your head that at the very least you wanna achieve a certain goal, and keep repeating that. For example, if you're struggling with urges just tell yourself to hold them off until Thanksgiving. Once you do that you'll realize that the end of the challenge is only 6 days away. Go step by step, don't look at the long term.

Hopefully that made sense, but that's what's kept me in, besides you soldiers of course. Thanks again soldiers, keep on going, we're almost there! o7

I'm out. Not from edging, a lucid wet dream, or by doctor's orders, but by a nut of my own volition. This year's NNN felt less like a wacky internet challenge and more of a sad chore, especially with the subreddit being miserable for a bit with the "top comment decides my punishment" posts.  
I've decided this was the opportune day to end it. Did it to remind myself "it's supposed to be a fun challenge, the posts shouldn't influence you how depressing it'd be if you'd lose this far". I imagined winning this year would leave an empty feeling in me, so I might as well quit and start early. The post-nut clarity didn't actually make me feel too bad. I'll still be continuing till the 22nd of December to recuperate from this deliberate loss.   
Memes were nice though. This year it took a femboy, a leather couch, and Amy Schumer to defeat a few of ours, but personally I don't think three of those combined could even top last year's Thanksgiving turkey.  
To those cumrades who are still-in and hell-bent in seeing the end of the month: Keep going, it should be a guaranteed win at this point. o7

Capt. Hector's Log book. November 22nd, 1887:

Of course, learning from my mistake last time I bought many more clothes to counteract the biting frost of the north. I set sail on Fallen Angel without a clear destination, for I never seen Frostfound myself, with whispers of rumors be my only guide.

"We're near Frostfound," Says the Sigil-Ridden Navigator after a few hours of sailing. Indeed, for few minutes later a grand palace of ice came into view, towers and ramps and galleries and stairs of ice, raised and spun like an architect's honey-dream. No spider ever wove so complex a web. The towers are utterly pristine, untouched by human life, but a pitiable encampment squats by the dock.

There, on the docks, a Riddlefisher who's wearing the blue-and-red scarf. My contact. I groan. Of course it has to be the Riddlefisher. What are the odds that I'll get a straight answer? 

Apparently not a lot, I discovered. Because all that bastard's giving me is a headache. I give up, the Admiralty can get his own damn answers. Before I storm back to the ship the Tireless Mechanic pulls me aside.

"Captain," He whispers. "I had a dream. A dream of the Stone Pigs, and the secret of how the Bazaar travels between the stars. The Fingerkings recruited me. They crack the dreams while I stole the secrets. The secrets on how to build the engine the Zee's never seen"

I still don't see where he's going with this, and my confusion must've shown on my face, because he continues. "This place holds the secrets, Captain. Please enter the castle with me and retrieve the secrets in there, I beg you" He pleads. I was about to decline such foolish request, but then I paused. My curiosity of what lies inside Frostfound grows strong. In the end, I agree to enter Frostfound with him. He clasps my shoulders. "Thank you thank you thank you!" Before he composes himself.

I prayed to Salt, Storm, and Stone that I will survive this voyage, for the deep dark zee is unforgiving.
